questionnaire.Unnamed: 3: Question

We are clear about the market that we are targeting for our product or service. This means that we can identify by name at least some of our potential customers, partners, suppliers, competitors and regulators.

We understand how value creation activity is distributed among the various players within our target market space and have worked out our role and what value we create for customers and other players in the market space.
We know how long it will take to establish a dominant position for our product or service in our chosen market space.
We are aware of the drivers that influence our market space in the areas of market, customer behaviour, technology, regulation and competition.
We are aware of the regulatory requirements that need to be satisfied to operate in our market space.

We understand how to uniquely frame the value proposition offered by our product or service for our target market space (e.g. low cost, high performance, best technology, ease of use, less competition etc.).
We have clearly identified our target customer types (i.e. consumers, professional users, businesses, government organisations).
We know our customers' specific needs and we are confident that our product or service can address.
We have accurately estimated the size of the addressable market in terms of the target customers (i.e. the segment where our product or service can be targeted at) for our chosen market space.
We have identified our most important market entry challenges e.g. product management, pricing, marketing & sales, channels and post-sales support, and understand their associated costs.
We know what our main channels to market are (direct, distributors, franchisees, agents etc.) and prioritised them in order of importance to help reach our target customers.
We understand the primary sales process that helps sell our product or service to our target customers.

questionnaire.Unnamed: 1: I1. Tech. Development and Contingent Deployment
questionnaire.Unnamed: 3: We understand which advantages of our innovative technology are most relevant to delivering our solution for the target application.
We understand how the building blocks that make up our solution, from technologies to platforms, products and services fit together - including those developed by other players.
We have a clear deployment strategy when implementing our solution (including the role of partners, suppliers and other service providers).

questionnaire.Unnamed: 2: IP Typology for Science and Technology Firms
questionnaire.Unnamed: 3: We are aware of all forms of IP (e.g. patents, trademarks / copyrights and knowhow) and how to protect them appropriately in the markets in which we operate.
We have a clear, comprehensive and validated IP strategy that provides us with freedom to operate.
We have strong and defensible IP that underpins our product or service.

questionnaire.Unnamed: 1: I3. Product & Service Definition and Synthesis
questionnaire.Unnamed: 2: Approach to Product and Service design
questionnaire.Unnamed: 3: We understand whether our product or service concept is driven by customer pull, technology push or some mix of push vs pull.
We understand the impact of all the components which make up our product or service.
We have a strong product management focus; understanding all the key components that make up our final product or service, and how they relate to each other.
We understand our overall manufacturing and deployment needs including regulations and supply chain considerations.
The delivery of our product or service can be achieved using existing manufacturing and operational processes and within existing regulations.
We have proven our manufacturing and deployment approach at commercial volumes and have worked out the associated economics.
We have effective access to all the core competences required to deliver our growth plans through our team including partners and suppliers.
All team members’ roles are inspiring and  mapped against key operational and delivery processes.
Our leadership style and culture are open, inclusive, energising and support the delivery of our growth plans.
We understand the various sources of funding (e.g., own resources, grants, debt, investors and customers) available for our business and we know how to access them.
We have a clear and appropriate funding strategy in place to support our growth plans.
We understand the risk / return profile of our business and how that relates to team and investor expectations.
We understand the overall commercial environment that we operate in, including the key (geo)political, environmental, regulatory, cultural factors and the pace of evolution of this environment.
We understand the disruptive forces in our market space, including new technologies, business models and entrants.
We have a well-considered strategic position for our product or service in our market space(s) including clear priorities that drive our execution effort.
We are aware of business models relevant to our product or service, and their underlying logic of value creation activities.
Our business model has been validated with customers and we fully understand the drivers for revenues, costs and profit margins.
We are tracking and improving our execution performance using relevant metrics derived from our business and revenue models.

help.Unnamed: 1: The Navigator tool offers a quick introduction to the Triple Chasm approach to commercialising science and technology enabled innovation; the first step in applying the systematic and powerful framework to businesses on the commercialisation journey.

If you are an entrepreneur, senior executive or an advisor of a business commercialising a novel science or technology based idea, this is an ideal tool to get an initial view of your existing commercialisation situation relative to the Triple Chasm 12 key considerations (Vectors) as it provides:
   • A benchmark against 304 successfully commercialised products (part of over 3000 products that were studied in the development      
      of Triple Chasm Model). 
   • A starting point to deciding where effort should be focussed next.
How do I use the Navigator?
Complete the PROFILE, respond to the QUESTIONAIRE then use the results on the DASHBOARD to get an initial understanding about where your effort should be focussed next.
If you have a team, getting them to join you in this process can help establish an aligned view of where the business is and what actions need to be taken to move it forward.

The Commercialisation Intensity on the DASHBOARD maps your self-assessment for each Vector (thick solid red line) against the average Intensity data from 304 successfully commercialised products / services around the world at the selected stage of Maturity (thin dashed red line).
The Vector Status and Next Steps windows on the DASHDOARD offer insight and guidance for your next steps along the commercialisation journey.
Get in touch with us if you have any questions or require further support.
